## 1. Test Coverage

- New features must include appropriate tests
- Bug fixes should include regression tests
- UI components should have snapshot tests
- Critical business logic must have unit tests
- Data fetching and API interactions should have mocked tests

## 2. Test Structure

### 2.1 Unit Tests

### 2.2 Integration Tests

- Focus on component interactions
- Test user flows and journeys
- Verify that components work together correctly
- Mock external dependencies but test internal interactions

### 2.3 End-to-End Tests

- Test critical user flows from start to finish
- Run against a test environment when possible
- Include authentication flows where applicable
- Test error handling and edge cases

## 3. Testing Tools

### 3.1 Component Testing

- Use React Testing Library for component tests
- Follow the "test behavior, not implementation" principle
- Test accessibility concerns
- Use mock service workers for API mocking

### 3.2 Performance Testing

- Include load time metrics for critical pages
- Test component rendering performance
- Monitor and test bundle size
- Test application under various network conditions

## 4. Test Maintainability

- Keep tests DRY with shared fixtures and setup
- Use descriptive test names
- Organize tests to mirror the structure of the code they're testing
- Avoid brittle tests that break with minor UI changes

## 5. Test-Driven Development

When applicable, follow a test-driven development approach:

1. Write failing tests first
2. Implement the minimal code to make tests pass
3. Refactor while ensuring tests still pass